# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: block-and-tackle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The **American Petroleum Institute** (**API**) is the largest U.S. trade association for the oil and natural gas industry.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] It claims to represent nearly 600 corporations involved in production, refinement, distribution, and many other aspects of the petroleum industry.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] It has advanced climate change denial and blocking of climate legislation to defend the interests of its constituent organizations.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The association describes its mission as "to promote safety across the industry globally and influence public policy in support of a strong, viable U.S. oil and natural gas industry".
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API's chief functions on behalf of the industry include advocacy, negotiation and lobbying with governmental, legal, and regulatory agencies; research into economic, toxicological, and environmental effects; establishment and certification of industry standards; and education outreach.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API both funds and conducts research related to many aspects of the petroleum industry.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Although some oil was produced commercially before 1859 as a byproduct from salt brine wells, the American oil industry started on a major scale with the discovery of oil at the Drake Well in western Pennsylvania in 1859.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The American Petroleum Institute was founded on March 20, 1919, and based in New York City.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In 1959, at a symposium organized by the American Petroleum Institute and the Columbia Graduate School of Business for the centennial of the American oil industry, the physicist Edward Teller warned then of the danger of global climate change.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Edward Teller explained that carbon dioxide "in the atmosphere causes a greenhouse effect" and that burning more fossil fuels could "melt the icecap and submerge New York".
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In 1969, the API decided to move its offices to Washington, DC.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API Standards Committees are made up of subcommittees and task groups that works and maintain these standards.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API also defines the industry standard for the energy conservation of motor oil.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] As of 2020 **API SP** is the latest specification.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] SP specifies more stringent engine oil performance requirements for spark-ignited internal combustion engines.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] These include a chain wear test and a test for very low-viscosity engine oils.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The standards also include a test designed to protect against a phenomenon experienced by some gasoline engines known as Low-Speed Pre-Ignition (LSPI).
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API also defines and drafts standards for measurement for manufactured products.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Crude Oil Data Exchange (CODE) is the electronic business standard as of 1978.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API RP 500 and RP 505 classify the locations for electrical equipment in hazardous areas.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In addition to training industry workers and conducting seminars, workshops, and conferences on public policy, API develops and distributes materials and curricula for schoolchildren and educators.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The association also maintains a website, *Classroom Energ*y.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API spent more than $3 million annually during the period 2005 to 2009 on lobbying.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] As of 2009, according to API’s quarterly “Lobbying Report” submitted to the U.S.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Senate, the organization had 16 lobbyists lobbying Congress.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The American Petroleum Institute also lobbied the State Department every quarter in 2009.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In three of four quarters, the group listed “legislative efforts concerning oil sands” as one of the areas it was focusing on in its lobbying, and in the final quarter, it listed “Canadian Oil Sands.” Among API’s members are ExxonMobil, which has invested in Canadian oil sands.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API lobbies and organizes its member employees' attendance at public events to communicate the industry's position on issues.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] A leaked summer 2009 memo from then API President Jack Gerard asked its member companies to urge their employees to participate in planned protests (designed to appear independently organized) against the cap-and-trade legislation the House passed that same summer.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] "The objective of these rallies is to put a human face on the impacts of unsound energy policy and to aim a loud message at [20 different] states," including Florida, Georgia, and Pennsylvania.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Gerard went on to assure recipients of the memo that API will cover all organizational costs and handling of logistics.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In response to the memo, an API spokesman told media that participants will be there (at protests) because of their own concerns, and that API is just helping them assemble.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] To help fight climate control legislation that has been approved by the U.S.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] House, API supports the Energy Citizens group, which is holding public events.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] API encouraged energy company employees to attend one of its first Energy Citizen events held in Houston in August 2009, but turned away Texas residents who were not employed by the energy industry.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] *Fast Company* reported that some attendees had no idea of the purpose of the event.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In December 2009, *Mother Jones* magazine said API and Energy Citizens were promulgating climate disinformation.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In January 2012, the American Petroleum Institute launched the voter education campaign – Vote 4 Energy.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The campaign says that increased domestic energy production can create jobs, increase government revenue, and provide U.S. energy security.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The Vote 4 Energy campaign does not promote any specific candidate or party, but rather provides voters with energy information to equip them to evaluate candidates on the federal and local levels and make decisions in favor of domestic energy on Election Day.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The main components of the Vote 4 Energy campaign include the website – Vote4Energy.org – and social media communities, along with a series of advertisements and events around the country.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The Vote 4 Energy campaign was criticized for presenting misleading arguments about the relationship between oil production and jobs whilst ignoring the potentially catastrophic consequences of increased fossil fuel consumption on the Earth's climate.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The API successfully pushed for an end to a ban on American oil exports on the grounds that the ban increased demand for Russian and Iranian oil, thereby benefiting the unfriendly regimes in these countries.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Critics noted that many of its member companies continued to maintain ongoing business in these countries whilst the lobbying campaign was in progress, leading to accusations of hypocrisy.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Furthermore, the API's campaigns have been criticized for advocating policies that are likely to exacerbate global warming and its associated problems.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The API has repeatedly funded conservative groups that deny the reality of anthropogenic global warming in spite of the overwhelming scientific consensus that it presents a serious problem for the planet.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] It has many front groups, including the NH Energy Forum that in August 2011 hosted a New Hampshire event for Republican presidential candidate Rick Perry.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In March 2022, the Climate Committee of the API reportedly approved a draft proposal urging Congress to pass a carbon tax on fossil fuels.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The draft proposal is subject to further approval by the API Executive Committee.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The proposal calls for gasoline wholesalers, power plants and others to pay a tax of $35 to $50 per ton of carbon dioxide generated by the fossil fuel they sell or use.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The proposal drew criticism amid coincident high prices at the pump and elsewhere.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In June 2021, in a sting operation carried out by *Unearthed*, senior ExxonMobil lobbyist Keith McCoy revealed that the company was 'for a carbon tax' because 'it gives us a talking point'.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In reality, McCoy stated, a carbon tax 'is not gonna happen'.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] In February 2015, it was revealed that climate denier Willie Soon had been paid by several fossil fuel interest groups.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Over the course of 14 years, he had received a total of $1.25m from Exxon Mobil, Southern Company, the American Petroleum Institute (API) and a foundation run by the libertarian Koch brothers, the documents obtained by Greenpeace show.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] The scientist described his studies to fossil fuel executives as "deliverables", and permitted anonymous pre-publication reviews.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Soon advanced the widely discredited theory that changes in solar activity are to blame for climate change, and called into question the severity and extent of climate change in all his studies, never revealing his backers.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] Every Tuesday (unless Monday is a holiday) at 4:30 PM the API releases a report on US inventories of crude oil, gasoline and distillates, to paid subscribers.
[src:block-and-tackle/american-petroleum-institute] As this information predates the report on the same inventory levels by the Energy Information Administration (EIA), it gives investors an early look at the information that may be coming from the EIA, although there is frequently some disparity between the two sets of figures.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] In knot tying, a **bight** is a curved section or slack part between the two ends of a rope, string, or yarn.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] A knot that can be tied using only the bight of a rope, without access to the ends, is described as **in the bight**.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] The term "bight" is also used in a more specific way when describing Turk's head knots, indicating how many repetitions of braiding are made in the circuit of a given knot.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] Sources differ on whether an open loop or U-shaped curve in a rope qualifies as a bight.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] Ashley (1944) treats bights and loops as distinct, stating that a curve "no narrower than a semicircle" is a bight, while an open loop is a curve "narrower than a bight but with separated ends".
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] In order to make a **slipped knot** (also **slipped loop** and **quick release knot**), a bight must be passed, rather than the end.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] This **slipped** form of the knot is more easily untied.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] The traditional bow knot used for tying shoelaces is simply a reef knot with the final overhand knot made with two bights instead of the ends.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] Similarly, a slippery hitch is a slipped variation of the single hitch that spills instantly when the end of the rope is pulled.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] The phrase **in the bight** (or **on a bight**) means a bight of line is itself being used to make a knot.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] Specifically this means that the knot can be formed without access to the ends of the rope.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] This can be an important property for knots to be used in situations where the ends of the rope are inaccessible, such as forming a fixed loop in the middle of a long climbing rope.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] Many knots normally tied with an end also have a form which is tied in the bight (for example, the bowline and the bowline on a bight).
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] In other cases, a knot being tied in the bight is a matter of the method of tying rather than a difference in the completed form of the knot.
[src:block-and-tackle/bight-knot] For example, the clove hitch can be made "in the bight" if it is being slipped over the end of a post or into an open carabiner but not if being cast onto a closed ring, which requires access to an end of the rope.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] A **block and tackle**, only **tackle** or **purchase** is a system of two or more pulleys with a rope or cable threaded between them, used to provide tension and lift heavy loads.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The pulleys are assembled to form blocks and then blocks are paired so that one is fixed and one moves with the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The rope is threaded through the pulleys to provide mechanical advantage that amplifies the force applied to the rope.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Hero of Alexandria described cranes formed from assemblies of pulleys in the first century.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Illustrated versions of Hero's *Mechanica* (a book on raising heavy weights) show early block and tackle systems.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] A block is a set of pulleys or sheaves mounted on a single frame.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] An assembly of blocks with a rope threaded through the pulleys is called tackle.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The process of threading ropes or cables through blocks is called "**reeving**", and a threaded block and tackle is said to have been "rove".
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] A block and tackle system amplifies the tension force in the rope to lift heavy loads.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] They are common on boats and sailing ships, where tasks are often performed manually, as well as on cranes and drilling rigs, where once rove, the tasks are performed by heavy equipment.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Note that in the gun tackle, double tackle and threefold purchase, both blocks have the same number of pulleys (one, two and three, respectively) whereas the Luff tackle and Gyn tackle have mis-matched blocks with differing numbers of pulleys.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] A block and tackle is characterized by the use of a single continuous rope to transmit a tension force around one or more pulleys to lift or move a load.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Its mechanical advantage is the number of parts of the rope that act on the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The mechanical advantage of a tackle dictates how much easier it is to haul or lift the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] If frictional losses are neglected, the mechanical advantage of a block and tackle is equal to the number of parts in the line that either attach to or run through the moving blocks—in other words, the number of supporting rope sections.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] An ideal block and tackle with a moving block supported by *n* rope sections has the mechanical advantage (MA), $MA={\frac {F_{B}}{F_{A}}}=n,\!$ where FA is the hauling (or input) force and FB is the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Consider the set of pulleys that form the moving block and the parts of the rope that support this block.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Ideal mechanical advantage correlates directly with velocity ratio.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The velocity ratio of a tackle is the ratio between the velocity of the hauling line to that of the hauled load.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] A line with a mechanical advantage of 4 has a velocity ratio of 4:1.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] In other words, to raise a load at 1 metre per second, the hauling part of the rope must be pulled at 4 metres per second.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Therefore, the mechanical advantage of a double tackle is 4.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The mechanical advantage of any tackle can be increased by interchanging the fixed and moving blocks so the rope is pulled in the direction of the load movement.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Diagram 3 shows three rope parts supporting the load *W*, which means the tension in the rope is *W/3*.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Thus, the mechanical advantage is three-to-one.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] By adding a pulley to the fixed block of a gun tackle the direction of the pulling force is reversed though the mechanical advantage remains the same, Diagram 3a.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The decision of which to use depends on pragmatic considerations for the total ergonomics of working with a particular situation.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Reeving to advantage is the most efficient use of equipment and resources.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] For example, if the load is to be hauled parallel to the ground, reeving to advantage enables the pulling force to be in the direction of the load movement, allowing obstacles to be managed more easily.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Reeving to disadvantage adds an extra sheave to change the direction of the pulling line to a potentially more ergonomic direction, which increases friction losses without improving the velocity ratio.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] This approximation is more accurate for smaller values of S and x .
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] A more precise estimate of efficiency is possible by use of the sheave friction factor, K (which may be obtainable from the manufacturer or published tables).
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Typical K values are 1.04 for roller bearing sheaves and 1.09 for plain bearing sheaves (with wire rope).
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] The increased force produced by a tackle is offset by both the increased length of rope needed and the friction in the system.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] In order to raise a block and tackle with a mechanical advantage of 6 a distance of 1 metre, it is necessary to pull 6 metres of rope through the blocks.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Frictional losses also mean there is a practical point at which the benefit of adding a further sheave is offset by the incremental increase in friction which would require additional force to be applied in order to lift the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Too much friction may result in the tackle not allowing the load to be released easily, or by the reduction in force needed to move the load being judged insufficient because undue friction has to be overcome as well.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] When installing a block on an existing line, it is often inconvenient at best to thread the rope through the block to be added.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] A swing cheek block is a special kind of block which can be opened to engage with a bight, without the necessity to thread the rope through the block or remove the load from the end of the rope.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] Examples of use (in an arboricultural setting) include: tail minding/tending, and for setting a rigging point in the tree above the cut to take place—a positive rigging situation.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-and-tackle] ) may include setting a block below the current cut, resulting in a 'negative' rigging situation, in which shock loads can be significant—especially if removing large sections of vertical stem.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] In sailing, a **block** is a single or multiple pulley.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] One or a number of *sheaves* are enclosed in an assembly between *cheeks* or *chocks*.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] In use, a block is fixed to the end of a line, to a spar, or to a surface.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] A line (rope) is *reeved* through the sheaves, and maybe through one or more matching blocks at some far end, to make up a tackle.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] The *purchase* of a tackle refers to its mechanical advantage.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] In general the more sheaves in the blocks that make up a tackle, the higher its mechanical advantage.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] The matter is slightly complicated by the fact that every tackle has a *working end* where the final run of rope leaves the last sheave.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] More mechanical advantage can be obtained if this end is attached to the moving load rather than the fixed end of the tackle.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] There are various types of blocks that are used in sailing.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] Some blocks are used to increase mechanical advantage and others are used simply to change the direction of a line.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] A *ratchet block* turns freely when a line is pulled in one direction but does not turn the other direction, although the line may slip past the sheave.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] This kind of block makes a loaded line easier to hold by hand, and is sometimes used on smaller boats for lines like main and jib sheets that are frequently adjusted.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] A single, large, sail-powered warship in the mid-19th century required more than 1,400 blocks of various kinds.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] Refers literally to the situation where pulling on the working line will not raise the load any further because the cheeks of one lifting block are already against the other.
[src:block-and-tackle/block-sailing] Figuratively this has come to mean that something is as full or as close as it can be.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] A **boat** is a watercraft of a large range of types and sizes, but generally smaller than a ship, which is distinguished by its larger size or capacity, its shape, or its ability to carry boats.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Small boats are typically used on inland waterways such as rivers and lakes, or in protected coastal areas.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] However, some boats (such as whaleboats) were intended for offshore use.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] In modern naval terms, a boat is a vessel small enough to be carried aboard a ship.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Submarines are referred to as *boats* rather than *ships* regardless of their size.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Boats vary in proportions and construction methods according to their intended purpose, available materials, or local traditions.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Canoes have been used since prehistoric times and remain in use throughout the world for transportation, fishing, and sport.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Fishing boats vary widely in style, partly to match local conditions.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Pleasure craft used in recreational boating include ski boats, pontoon boats, and sailboats.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Houseboats may be used for vacationing or long-term residence.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Lighters are used to move cargo to and from large ships unable to get close to shore.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Lifeboats have rescue and safety functions.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Boats can be propelled by manpower (e.g., rowboats and paddle boats), wind (e.g., sailboats), and inboard/outboard motors (including gasoline, diesel, and electric).
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The earliest watercraft are considered to have been rafts.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] These would have been used for voyages such as the settlement of Australia, which occurred sometime between 50,000 and 60,000 years ago.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] A boat differs from a raft by obtaining its buoyancy by having most of its structure exclude water with a waterproof layer, e.g., the planks of a wooden hull, the hide covering (or tarred canvas) of a currach.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] In contrast, a raft is buoyant because it joins components that are themselves buoyant, such as logs, bamboo poles, bundles of reeds, and floats (such as inflated hides, sealed pottery containers, or, in a modern context, empty oil drums).
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The key difference between a raft and a boat is that the former is a "flow through" structure, with waves able to pass up through it.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Consequently, except for short river crossings, a raft is not a practical means of transport in colder regions of the world, as the users would be at risk of hypothermia.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Today, that climatic limitation restricts rafts to between 40° north and 40° south, with similar boundaries in the past that have shifted as the world's climate has varied.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The earliest boats may have been either dugouts or hide boats.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The oldest recovered boat in the world, the Pesse canoe, found in the Netherlands, is a dugout made from the hollowed tree trunk of a *Pinus sylvestris* that was constructed somewhere between 8200 and 7600 BC.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] This canoe is exhibited in the Drents Museum in Assen, Netherlands.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Other very old dugout boats have also been recovered.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Hide boats, made from covering a framework with animal skins, could be equally as old as logboats, but such a structure is much less likely to survive in an archaeological context.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Plank-built boats are considered, in most cases, to have developed from the logboat.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] There are examples of logboats that have been expanded: by deforming the hull under heat, by raising the sides with added planks, or by splitting down the middle and adding a central plank to widen it.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] (Some of these methods have been in quite recent use – there is no simple developmental sequence).
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The earliest known plank-built boats are from the Nile, dating to the third millennium BC.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Outside Egypt, the next earliest are from England.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The Ferriby boats are dated to the early second millennium BC and the end of the third millennium BC.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Plank-built boats require a level of woodworking technology that was first available in the Neolithic with more complex versions only becoming achievable in the Bronze Age.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Boats can be categorized by their means of propulsion.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Powered by the crew-members on board, using oars, paddles or a punting pole or quant.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Towed – either by humans or animals from a river or canal bank (or in very shallow water, by walking on the sea or river bed) or by another vessel.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Powered by machinery, such as internal combustion engines, steam engines, or by batteries and an electric motor.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Any one vessel may use more than one of these methods at different times or in combination.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Several large vessels are usually referred to as boats.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Other types of large vessels which are traditionally called boats include Great Lakes freighters, riverboats, and ferryboats.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Though large enough to carry their own boats and heavy cargo, these vessels are designed for operation on inland or protected coastal waters.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The hull is the main, and in some cases only, structural component of a boat.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The keel is a boat's "backbone", a lengthwise structural member to which the perpendicular frames are fixed.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] On some boats, a deck covers the hull, in part or whole.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] While a ship often has several decks, a boat is unlikely to have more than one.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Above the deck are often lifelines connected to stanchions, bulwarks, perhaps topped by gunnels, or some combination of the two.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] A cabin may protrude above the deck forward, aft, along the centerline, or cover much of the length of the boat.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Vertical structures dividing the internal spaces are known as bulkheads.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] The forward end of a boat is called the bow, the aft end the stern.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Facing forward the right side is referred to as starboard and the left side as port.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Until the mid-19th century, most boats were made of natural materials, primarily wood, although bark and animal skins were also used.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Early boats include the birch bark canoe, the animal hide-covered kayak and coracle and the dugout canoe made from a single log.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] By the mid-19th century, some boats had been built with iron or steel frames but still planked in wood.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] In 1855, ferro-cement boat construction was patented by the French, who coined the name "ferciment".
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] This is a system by which a steel or iron wire framework is built in the shape of a boat's hull and covered over with cement.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Reinforced with bulkheads and other internal structures, it is strong but heavy, easily repaired, and, if sealed properly, will not leak or corrode.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] As the forests of Britain and Europe continued to be over-harvested to supply the keels of larger wooden boats, and the Bessemer process (patented in 1855) reduced the cost of steel, steel ships and boats became more common.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] By the 1930s, boats built entirely of steel, from frames to plating, were replacing wooden boats in many industrial uses and fishing fleets.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Private recreational steel boats remain uncommon.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] In 1895, WH Mullins produced steel boats of galvanized iron, and by 1930, became the world's largest producer of pleasure boats.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Mullins also offered aluminium boats from 1895 through 1899 and once again in the 1920s, but it was not until the mid-20th century that aluminium gained widespread popularity.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Though much more expensive than steel, certain aluminum alloys do not corrode in salt water, allowing them to carry loads comparable to steel at much lower weight.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Around the mid-1960s, boats made of fiberglass (aka "glass fiber") became popular, especially for recreational boats.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Fiberglass is also known as "GRP" (glass-reinforced plastic) in the UK and "FRP" (fiber-reinforced plastic) in the US.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Fiberglass boats are strong and do not rust, corrode, or rot.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Instead, they are susceptible to structural degradation from sunlight and temperature extremes over their lifespan.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Fiberglass structures can be made stiffer with sandwich panels, where the fiberglass encloses a lightweight core such as balsa wood or foam.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Cold molding is a modern construction method that uses wood as the structural component.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] In a single cold-molding process, very thin strips of wood are layered over a form.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Each layer is coated with resin, then another layer is laid on top at a 90-degree angle.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Subsequent layers may be stapled or otherwise mechanically fastened to the previous layer, or weighted or vacuum-bagged to provide compression and stabilization until the resin sets.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] An alternative process uses thin plywood sheets shaped over a disposable male mold and coated with epoxy.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] A boat displaces its weight in water, regardless of whether it is made of wood, steel, fiberglass, or even concrete.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] If weight is added to the boat, the volume of the hull submerged below the waterline will increase to keep the weight above and below the surface balanced.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Boats have a natural or designed level of buoyancy.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Exceeding it will cause the boat first to ride lower in the water, second to take on water more readily than when properly loaded, and ultimately, if overloaded by any combination of structure, cargo, and water, sink.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] As commercial vessels must be correctly loaded to be safe, and as the sea becomes less buoyant in brackish areas such as the Baltic, the Plimsoll line was introduced to prevent overloading.
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Since 1998, all new leisure boats and barges built in Europe between 2.5m and 24m must comply with the EU's Recreational Craft Directive (RCD).
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] Europe is the main producer of recreational boats (the second-largest producer in the world is Poland).
[src:block-and-tackle/boat] European brands are known all over the world – in fact, these are the brands that created RCD and set the standard for shipyards around the world.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The word comes from the German *Karabiner*, short for *Karabinerhaken*, meaning "carbine hook," as the device was used by carabiniers to attach their carbines to their belts.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Carabiners are widely used in rope-intensive activities such as climbing, fall arrest systems, arboriculture, caving, sailing, hot-air ballooning, rope rescue, construction, industrial rope work, window cleaning, whitewater rescue, and acrobatics.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] They are predominantly made from both steel and aluminium.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Those used in sports tend to be of a lighter weight than those used in commercial applications and rope rescue.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Often referred to as carabiner-style or as mini-carabiners, carabiner keyrings and other light-use clips of similar style and design have also become popular.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Most are stamped with a "not for climbing" or similar warning due to a common lack of load-testing and safety standards in manufacturing.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] While any metal link with a spring-loaded gate is technically a carabiner, the strict usage among the climbing community specifically refers only to devices manufactured and tested for load-bearing in safety-critical systems like rock and mountain climbing, typically rated to 20 kN or more.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Carabiners on hot-air balloons are used to connect the envelope to the basket and are rated at 2.5, 3, or 4 tonnes.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Load-bearing screw-gate carabiners are used to connect the diver's umbilical to the surface supplied diver's harness.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] They are usually rated for a safe working load of 5 kN or more (equivalent to a weight in excess of approximately 500 kg).
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] D: Asymmetric shape transfers the majority of the load on to the spine, the carabiner's strongest axis.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Offset-D: Variant of a D with a greater asymmetry, allowing for a wider gate opening.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Pear/HMS: Wider and rounder shape at the top than offset-D's, and typically larger.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Used for belaying with a munter hitch, and with some types of belay device.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The largest HMS carabiners can also be used for rappelling with a munter hitch (the size is needed to accommodate the hitch with two strands of rope).
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] These are usually the heaviest carabiners.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Carabiners fall into three broad locking categories: non-locking, manual locking, and auto locking.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Non-locking carabiners (or *snap-links*) have a sprung swinging gate that accepts a rope, webbing sling, or other hardware.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Rock climbers frequently connect two non-locking carabiners with a short length of webbing to create a quickdraw (an extender).
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Wire gate: A single piece of bent spring-steel wire forms the gate.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Wire gate carabiners are significantly lighter than solid gates, with roughly the same strength.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Wire gates are less prone to icing up than solid gates, an advantage in Alpine mountaineering and ice climbing.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Simple wiregate designs feature a notch that can snag objects (similar to original solid gate designs), but newer designs feature a shroud or guide wires around the "hooked" part of the carabiner nose to prevent snagging.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Both solid and wire gate carabiners can be either "straight gate" or "bent gate".
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Bent-gate carabiners are easier to clip a rope into using only one hand, and so are often used for the rope-end carabiner of quickdraws and alpine draws used for lead climbing.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Locking carabiners have the same general shape as non-locking carabiners, but have an additional mechanism securing the gate to prevent unintentional opening during use.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] These mechanisms may be either threaded sleeves ("screw-lock"), spring-loaded sleeves ("twist-lock"), magnetic levers ("Magnetron"), other spring loaded unlocking levers or opposing double spring loaded gates ("twin-gate").
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] American National Standards Institute/American Society of Safety Engineers standard ANSI Z359.1-2007 *Safety Requirement for Personal Fall Arrest Systems, Subsystems and Components*, section 3.2.1.4 (for snap hooks and carabiners) is a voluntary consensus standard.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] This standard requires that all connectors/ carabiners support a minimum breaking strength (MBS) of 5,000 lbf (22 kN) and feature an auto-locking gate mechanism which supports a minimum breaking strength (MBS) of 3,600 lbf (16 kN).
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The first known hooks that had a sprung, hinged gate where the spring kept it closed (characteristics expected of a carabiner) were depicted by Nuremberg patrician Martin Löffelholz von Kolberg in about 1505 in the Codex Löffelholz, in the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] These then became the clip used to hold a cavalry carbine or arquebus, with the earliest known mention of them being in 1616 by Johann Jacob von Wallhausen in the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] They were widely used in many European countries during the 17th century, and typically had a belt attachment and swivel joint, much like a modern luggage strap or handbag strap.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The load bearing latch was added in the 1790s, for the British cavalry design.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] They were used for many other purposes during the 19th century, such as for luggage straps, mining and connecting ropes.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Some common designs first appeared during that time, including S-carabiners.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Oval links, which had also appeared in 1485, also reappeared as carabiners.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Screw gates and internal springs were developed.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Prussian fire brigades began to use carabiners for connecting themselves to ladders in 1847, and this became the modern gourd-shaped design by 1868.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] German and Austrian mountaineers started using them during the late 19th century, with a mention of their use from 1879, and their continued use for climbing by climbers in Saxon Switzerland.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The majority used gourd shaped carabiners which were created for mining or other utility purposes.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The common myth suggesting that mountaineering carabiners were invented or made by German climber Otto "Rambo" Herzog in the 1910s has no basis in fact.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] He used them for some challenging climbs and some new techniques at a time when such "artificial aids" were still controversial in mountain climbing, but he did not invent them or develop any designs, and he was born long after other climbers were already using carabiners.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] During the 1920s many designs were used by mountain climbers, such as gourd-shaped, oval or elliptical, mostly sold for general hardware.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] By the early 1930s, a form of carabiner were being sold for climbing, oval designs being the most popular.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] During this decade, hardened steel carabiners appeared and the first aluminium carabiner prototypes were made by Pierre Allain, although they were never sold.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The modern carabiner that endures today was first designed and widely distributed during WWII for the US Army.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Raffi Bedayn, an engineer from the San Francisco Bay Area was assigned the project to meet a need for swift, strong and secure rope attachments for use by the infantry.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Bedayn was one of the early "golden age" Yosemite mountain climbers with years of involvement with the American Alpine Club and drew on his experience to inform his design.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Bedayn crafted a smooth steel oval with a spring-operated lever opening (or "gate") and a rod-and-hook gate closure that imbeds in the carabiner body to prevent twisting, a design still in use today.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Bedayn innovated the use of lighter aluminum when steel became scarce during the war.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Early carabiners from Bedayn's commercial production efforts during the late 1940s - 1960s have "Bedayn California" or "Bedayn Calif." engraved on the gate or on one end of the oval.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] These were the first commercially produced carabiners designed specifically for climbing.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Later innovations included offset D-shaped carabiners and locking mechanisms.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Rock climbers such as Yvon Chouinard were credited for ongoing evolutionary adaptions of the basic design - such as the "D shape" carabiner and locking features, which facilitated better safety and stability during climbs.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Aluminium carabiners were first sold to the military in 1941, which were the first commercial carabiners designed specifically for climbing.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Slightly offset D-shaped carabiners were sold in the late 1940s, which became the standard offset D-shape (which is now the most common) in the 1950s.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Chouinard Equipment introduced the 22 kN aluminium carabiner in 1968, though this strength had already been far surpassed by steel carabiners.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] Wiregate carabiners were first patented in 1969, and were sold for maritime use.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] They were first sold for climbing in 1996.
[src:block-and-tackle/carabiner] The popular keylock, which avoids snagging, was developed around 1984–1987.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] A **crane** is a machine used to move materials both vertically and horizontally, utilizing a system of a boom, hoist, wire ropes or chains, and sheaves for lifting and relocating heavy objects within the swing of its boom.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The device uses one or more simple machines, such as the lever and pulley, to create mechanical advantage to do its work.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Cranes are commonly employed in transportation for the loading and unloading of freight, in construction for the movement of materials, and in manufacturing for the assembling of heavy equipment.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The first known crane machine was the shaduf, a water-lifting device that was invented in ancient Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) and then appeared in ancient Egyptian technology.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Construction cranes later appeared in ancient Greece, where they were powered by men or animals (such as donkeys), and used for the construction of buildings.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Larger cranes were later developed in the Roman Empire, employing the use of human treadwheels, permitting the lifting of heavier weights.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In the High Middle Ages, harbour cranes were introduced to load and unload ships and assist with their construction—some were built into stone towers for extra strength and stability.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The earliest cranes were constructed from wood, but cast iron, iron and steel took over with the coming of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For many centuries, power was supplied by the physical exertion of men or animals, although hoists in watermills and windmills could be driven by the harnessed natural power.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The first *mechanical* power was provided by steam engines, the earliest steam crane being introduced in the 18th or 19th century, with many remaining in use well into the late 20th century.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Modern cranes usually use internal combustion engines or electric motors and hydraulic systems to provide a much greater lifting capability than was previously possible, although manual cranes are still utilized where the provision of power would be uneconomic.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] There are many different types of cranes, each tailored to a specific use.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Sizes range from the smallest jib cranes, used inside workshops, to the tallest tower cranes, used for constructing high buildings.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Mini-cranes are also used for constructing high buildings, to facilitate constructions by reaching tight spaces.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Large floating cranes are generally used to build oil rigs and salvage sunken ships.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Some lifting machines do not strictly fit the above definition of a crane, but are generally known as cranes, such as stacker cranes and loader cranes.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Cranes were so called from the resemblance to the long neck of the bird, cf.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The earliest known lifting device was the *shadoof*, a crane-like device used in Mesopotamia around 3000 BCE, which had a lever mechanism and was used for irrigation purposes.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] It was invented in Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) circa 3000 BC.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The shadouf subsequently appeared in ancient Egyptian technology circa 2000 BC.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] However, the transition to building cranes occurred in ancient Greece during the late 6th century BCE.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Archaeological evidence, including distinctive cuttings for lifting tongs and Lewis irons on stone blocks of Greek temples, indicates a fundamental shift in engineering strategy coinciding with the development of the Greek city-state (*polis*).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This labor constraint necessitated mechanical advantage provided by the winch and pulley system, replacing labor-intensive ramps.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In contrast to the archaic period with its pattern of ever-increasing block sizes, Greek temples of the classical age like the Parthenon invariably featured stone blocks weighing less than 15–20 metric tons.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Also, the practice of erecting large monolithic columns was practically abandoned in favour of using several column drums.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The first unequivocal literary evidence for the existence of the compound pulley system appears in the *Mechanical Problems* (*Mech*.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] 18, 853a32–853b13) attributed to Aristotle (384–322 BC), but perhaps composed at a slightly later date.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Around the same time, block sizes at Greek temples began to match their archaic predecessors again, indicating that the more sophisticated compound pulley must have found its way to Greek construction sites by then.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The heyday of the crane in ancient times came during the Roman Empire, when construction activity soared and buildings reached enormous dimensions.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The Romans adopted the Greek crane and developed it further.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] There is much available information about their lifting techniques, thanks to rather lengthy accounts by the engineers Vitruvius and Heron of Alexandria.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] There are also two surviving reliefs of Roman treadwheel cranes, with the Haterii tombstone from the late first century AD being particularly detailed.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Roman engineers advanced Greek designs by analyzing mechanical advantage ratios.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The simplest Roman crane, the *trispastos*, consisted of a double-beam jib, a winch, a rope, and a block containing three pulleys.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Having thus a mechanical advantage of 3:1, it has been calculated that a single man working the winch could raise 150 kg (330 lb) (3 pulleys x 50 kg or 110 lb = 150), assuming that 50 kg (110 lb) represent the maximum effort a man can exert over a longer time period.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Heavier crane types featured five pulleys (*pentaspastos*) or, in case of the largest one, a set of three by five pulleys (*Polyspastos*) and came with two, three or four masts, depending on the maximum load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The *polyspastos* represented a major leap in mechanical efficiency.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] When worked by four men at both sides of the winch, it could readily lift 3,000 kg (6,600 lb) (3 ropes x 5 pulleys x 4 men x 50 kg or 110 lb = 3,000 kg or 6,600 lb).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] If the winch was replaced by a treadwheel, the maximum load could be doubled to 6,000 kg (13,000 lb) at only half the crew, since the treadwheel possesses a much bigger mechanical advantage due to its larger diameter.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] However, substituting the winch with a *treadwheel*—a large wooden wheel rotated by men walking inside it—doubled this capacity to 6,000 kg with half the crew.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This efficiency increase resulted from the treadwheel's larger diameter creating a much greater moment arm compared to a hand winch.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This system increased lifting efficiency by 60 times compared to Egyptian pyramid construction, where approximately 50 men were required to move a 2.5-tonne stone block up a ramp.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] However, numerous extant Roman buildings which feature much heavier stone blocks than those handled by the *polyspastos* indicate that the overall lifting capability of the Romans went far beyond that of any single crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] At the temple of Jupiter at Baalbek, for instance, the architrave blocks weigh up to 60 tons each, and one corner cornice block even over 100 tons, all of them raised to a height of about 19 m (62.3 ft).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In Rome, the capital block of Trajan's Column weighs 53.3 tons, which had to be lifted to a height of about 34 m (111.5 ft) (see construction of Trajan's Column).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Second, a multitude of capstans were placed on the ground around the tower, for, although having a lower leverage ratio than treadwheels, capstans could be set up in higher numbers and run by more men (and, moreover, by draught animals).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This use of multiple capstans is also described by Ammianus Marcellinus (17.4.15) in connection with the lifting of the Lateranense obelisk in the Circus Maximus (c.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The maximum lifting capability of a single capstan can be established by the number of lewis iron holes bored into the monolith.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In case of the Baalbek architrave blocks, which weigh between 55 and 60 tons, eight extant holes suggest an allowance of 7.5 ton per lewis iron, that is per capstan.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Lifting such heavy weights in a concerted action required a great amount of coordination between the work groups applying the force to the capstans.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] During the medieval period, Persian engineers advanced lifting technology significantly, bridging the gap between ancient mechanics and modern engineering.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Al-Jazari (1136–1206), working in the Artuqid court, documented revolutionary lifting mechanisms including early versions of the crankshaft, camshaft, and reciprocating pump in his *Book of Knowledge of Ingenious Mechanical Devices* (1206 CE).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] These innovations transformed water-lifting from manual systems to semi-automated mechanisms.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] During the High Middle Ages, the treadwheel crane was reintroduced on a large scale after the technology had fallen into disuse in western Europe with the demise of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The earliest reference to a treadwheel (*magna rota*) reappears in archival literature in France about 1225, followed by an illuminated depiction in a manuscript of probably also French origin dating to 1240.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In navigation, the earliest uses of harbor cranes are documented for Utrecht in 1244, Antwerp in 1263, Bruges in 1288 and Hamburg in 1291, while in England the treadwheel is not recorded before 1331.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Generally, vertical transport could be done more safely and inexpensively by cranes than by customary methods.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Typical areas of application were harbors, mines, and, in particular, building sites where the treadwheel crane played a pivotal role in the construction of the lofty Gothic cathedrals.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Nevertheless, both archival and pictorial sources of the time suggest that newly introduced machines like treadwheels or wheelbarrows did not completely replace more labor-intensive methods like ladders, hods and handbarrows.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Rather, old and new machinery continued to coexist on medieval construction sites and harbors.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Apart from treadwheels, medieval depictions also show cranes to be powered manually by windlasses with radiating spokes, cranks and by the 15th century also by windlasses shaped like a ship's wheel.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] To smooth out irregularities of impulse and get over 'dead-spots' in the lifting process flywheels are known to be in use as early as 1123.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The exact process by which the treadwheel crane was reintroduced is not recorded, although its return to construction sites has undoubtedly to be viewed in close connection with the simultaneous rise of Gothic architecture.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The reappearance of the treadwheel crane may have resulted from a technological development of the windlass from which the treadwheel structurally and mechanically evolved.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Alternatively, the medieval treadwheel may represent a deliberate reinvention of its Roman counterpart drawn from Vitruvius' *De architectura* which was available in many monastic libraries.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Its reintroduction may have been inspired, as well, by the observation of the labor-saving qualities of the waterwheel with which early treadwheels shared many structural similarities.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The medieval treadwheel was a large wooden wheel turning around a central shaft with a treadway wide enough for two workers walking side by side.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] While the earlier 'compass-arm' wheel had spokes directly driven into the central shaft, the more advanced "clasp-arm" type featured arms arranged as chords to the wheel rim, giving the possibility of using a thinner shaft and providing thus a greater mechanical advantage.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Contrary to a popularly held belief, cranes on medieval building sites were neither placed on the extremely lightweight scaffolding used at the time nor on the thin walls of the Gothic churches which were incapable of supporting the weight of both hoisting machine and load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Rather, cranes were placed in the initial stages of construction on the ground, often within the building.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] When a new floor was completed, and massive tie beams of the roof connected the walls, the crane was dismantled and reassembled on the roof beams from where it was moved from bay to bay during construction of the vaults.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Thus, the crane "grew" and "wandered" with the building with the result that today all extant construction cranes in England are found in church towers above the vaulting and below the roof, where they remained after building construction for bringing material for repairs aloft.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Less frequently, medieval illuminations also show cranes mounted on the outside of walls with the stand of the machine secured to putlogs.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In contrast to modern cranes, medieval cranes and hoists — much like their counterparts in Greece and Rome — were primarily capable of a vertical lift, and not used to move loads for a considerable distance horizontally as well.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Accordingly, lifting work was organized at the workplace in a different way than today.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In building construction, for example, it is assumed that the crane lifted the stone blocks either from the bottom directly into place, or from a place opposite the centre of the wall from where it could deliver the blocks for two teams working at each end of the wall.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Additionally, the crane master who usually gave orders at the treadwheel workers from outside the crane was able to manipulate the movement laterally by a small rope attached to the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Slewing cranes which allowed a rotation of the load and were thus particularly suited for dockside work appeared as early as 1340.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] While ashlar blocks were directly lifted by sling, lewis or devil's clamp (German *Teufelskralle*), other objects were placed before in containers like pallets, baskets, wooden boxes or barrels.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] It is noteworthy that medieval cranes rarely featured ratchets or brakes to forestall the load from running backward.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This curious absence is explained by the high friction force exercised by medieval tread-wheels which normally prevented the wheel from accelerating beyond control.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] According to the "present state of knowledge" unknown in antiquity, stationary harbor cranes are considered a new development of the Middle Ages.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The typical harbor crane was a pivoting structure equipped with double treadwheels.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] These cranes were placed docksides for the loading and unloading of cargo where they replaced or complemented older lifting methods like see-saws, winches and yards.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Dockside cranes were not adopted in the Mediterranean region and the highly developed Italian ports where authorities continued to rely on the more labor-intensive method of unloading goods by ramps beyond the Middle Ages.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Unlike construction cranes where the work speed was determined by the relatively slow progress of the masons, harbor cranes usually featured double treadwheels to speed up loading.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The two treadwheels whose diameter is estimated to be 4 m or larger were attached to each side of the axle and rotated together.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Their capacity was 2–3 tons, which apparently corresponded to the customary size of marine cargo.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Today, according to one survey, fifteen treadwheel harbor cranes from pre-industrial times are still extant throughout Europe.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Some harbour cranes were specialised at mounting masts to newly built sailing ships, such as in Gdańsk, Cologne and Bremen.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Beside these stationary cranes, floating cranes, which could be flexibly deployed in the whole port basin came into use by the 14th century.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] A sheer hulk (or shear hulk) was used in shipbuilding and repair as a floating crane in the days of sailing ships, primarily to place the lower masts of a ship under construction or repair.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Booms known as sheers were attached to the base of a hulk's lower masts or beam, supported from the top of those masts.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Blocks and tackle were then used in such tasks as placing or removing the lower masts of the vessel under construction or repair.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] These lower masts were the largest and most massive single timbers aboard a ship, and erecting them without the assistance of either a sheer hulk or land-based masting sheer was extremely difficult.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The concept of sheer hulks originated with the Royal Navy in the 1690s, and persisted in Britain until the early nineteenth century.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Most sheer hulks were decommissioned warships; *Chatham*, built in 1694, was the first of only three purpose-built vessels.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] There were at least six sheer hulks in service in Britain at any time throughout the 1700s.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The concept spread to France in the 1740s with the commissioning of a sheer hulk at the port of Rochefort.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] A lifting tower similar to that of the ancient Romans was used to great effect by the Renaissance architect Domenico Fontana in 1586 to relocate the 361 t heavy Vatican obelisk in Rome.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] From his report, it becomes obvious that the coordination of the lift between the various pulling teams required a considerable amount of concentration and discipline, since, if the force was not applied evenly, the excessive stress on the ropes would make them rupture.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Cranes were also used domestically during this period.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The chimney or fireplace crane was used to swing pots and kettles over the fire and the height was adjusted by a trammel.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] With the onset of the Industrial Revolution the first modern cranes were installed at harbours for loading cargo.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In 1838, the industrialist and businessman William Armstrong designed a water-powered hydraulic crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] His design used a ram in a closed cylinder that was forced down by a pressurized fluid entering the cylinder and a valve regulated the amount of fluid intake relative to the load on the crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This mechanism, the hydraulic jigger, then pulled on a chain to lift the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In 1845 a scheme was set in motion to provide piped water from distant reservoirs to the households of Newcastle.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Armstrong was involved in this scheme and he proposed to Newcastle Corporation that the excess water pressure in the lower part of town could be used to power one of his hydraulic cranes for the loading of coal onto barges at the Quayside.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] He claimed that his invention would do the job faster and more cheaply than conventional cranes.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The corporation agreed to his suggestion, and the experiment proved so successful that three more hydraulic cranes were installed on the Quayside.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The success of his hydraulic crane led Armstrong to establish the Elswick works at Newcastle, to produce his hydraulic machinery for cranes and bridges in 1847.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] His company soon received orders for hydraulic cranes from Edinburgh and Northern Railways and from Liverpool Docks, as well as for hydraulic machinery for dock gates in Grimsby.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The company expanded from a workforce of 300 and an annual production of 45 cranes in 1850, to almost 4,000 workers producing over 100 cranes per year by the early 1860s.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Armstrong spent the next few decades constantly improving his crane design; his most significant innovation was the hydraulic accumulator.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Where water pressure was not available on site for the use of hydraulic cranes, Armstrong often built high water towers to provide a supply of water at pressure.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] However, when supplying cranes for use at New Holland on the Humber Estuary, he was unable to do this, because the foundations consisted of sand.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] He eventually produced the hydraulic accumulator, a cast-iron cylinder fitted with a plunger supporting a very heavy weight.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The plunger would slowly be raised, drawing in water, until the downward force of the weight was sufficient to force the water below it into pipes at great pressure.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This invention allowed much larger quantities of water to be forced through pipes at a constant pressure, thus increasing the crane's load capacity considerably.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] One of his cranes, commissioned by the Italian Navy in 1883 and in use until the mid-1950s, is still standing in Venice, where it is now in a state of disrepair.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Crane design requires balancing three fundamental considerations: adequate load capacity, stability against tipping, and structural failure prevention.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Stability is achieved through moment equilibrium, where permitted loads are significantly less than tipping loads—typically 75-85% in the US and 70-80% in Europe.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Ground conditions critically affect stability, with outrigger pads exerting 50-200 kPa pressure.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The dynamic lift factor (DLF) accounts for transient forces from hoisting acceleration, crane motion, wave-induced vessel motions in offshore applications, and wind effects (20 m/s in-service, 42 m/s out-of-service).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Human factors and modern electronic control systems significantly influence dynamic loading.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] International standards including ASME B30.5 and EN 13000 establish safety requirements, while sophisticated instrumentation such as load cells, accelerometers, and strain gauges validate crane performance during type approval testing.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For stability, the sum of all moments about the base of the crane must be close to zero so that the crane does not overturn.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The principle of moment equilibrium (ΣM = 0) is fundamental to crane design, where M represents moments about the crane's center of rotation.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In practice, the magnitude of load that is permitted to be lifted (called the "rated load" in the United States) is some value less than the load that will cause the crane to tip, thus providing a safety margin.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Under United States standards for mobile cranes, the stability-limited rated load for a crawler crane is 75% of the tipping load, and for outrigger-supported cranes is 85% of the tipping load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] These requirements are established by the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in the volume ASME B30.5-2018 *Mobile and Locomotive Cranes*.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] European standards (EN 13000:2010) adopt similar principles but with different safety factors reflecting different regulatory philosophies regarding risk tolerance.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For mobile cranes on outriggers, the rated capacity under European standards is typically 80% of the tipping load, while crawler cranes are rated at 70% of the tipping load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Safety margins typically range between 10 and 25% above a crane's rated capacity.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] However, regular operation near or above rated capacity significantly increases wear on components, resulting in higher maintenance costs and shortened operational lifespan.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The design must account for fatigue cycles, with typical design life of 20 years or 2 million load cycles per ISO 12482-1:2014.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For mobile cranes on outriggers, stability depends critically on ground conditions.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The typical outrigger pad exerts pressures of 50-200 kPa (7-29 psi).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Engineering guidelines require soil bearing capacity assessments before crane setup, with mandatory use of timber mats or engineered cribbing when soil capacity is below 150 kPa.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Inadequate ground preparation is a leading cause of crane tipping accidents, particularly in construction sites with variable soil conditions.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Standards for cranes mounted on ships or offshore platforms are somewhat stricter because of the dynamic load on the crane due to vessel motion.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For loads not associated with crewed operations, allowable loads must factor in dynamic accelerations including 1.75 g vertical, 0.75 g longitudinal, and 0.75 g transverse acceleration, meaning a 2000 kg static load requires crane capacity for 3500 kg at sea.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Additionally, the stability of the vessel or platform must be considered.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For stationary pedestal or kingpost mounted cranes, the moment produced by the boom, jib, and load is resisted by the pedestal base or kingpost.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Stress within the base must be less than the yield stress of the material or the crane will fail.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The design must account for fatigue loading, wind-induced oscillations, and thermal expansion effects over the crane's operational lifetime.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The dynamic lift factor (DLF), also known as the design dynamic factor, is a critical parameter in crane design and operation.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] It accounts for the dynamic effects that can increase the load on a crane's structure and components during lifting operations.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] These effects include hoisting acceleration and deceleration of the load, crane movement such as slewing or luffing, swinging of suspended loads, wind forces acting on the crane, the load and the rigging, and operator error or other unexpected events.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The DLF for a new crane design can be determined with analytical calculations and mathematical models following the relevant design specifications.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] More sophisticated methods, such as finite element analysis or other simulation techniques, may also be used to model the crane's behavior under various loading conditions, as deemed appropriate by the designer or certifying authority.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] To verify the actual DLF, control load tests can be conducted on the completed crane using instrumentation such as load cells, accelerometers, and strain gauges.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] This process is usually part of the crane's type approval.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Jib cranes typically have a lower DLF ( ${\textstyle \psi \approx 1.3}$ ) compared to traveling gantry cranes ( $\psi \approx 1.6$ ) because they are stiffer.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For grab bucket cranes, the DLF can increase by 20% to 30% reflecting the shock loads caused by the release of the lifted material.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The DLF generally decreases as the mass of the lifted object increases, as cranes tend to operate at lower velocities with heavier loads to ensure safety and stability.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] In offshore lifting, where the crane and/or lifted object are on a floating vessel, the DLF is higher compared to onshore lifts because of the additional movement caused by wave action.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Wave-induced vessel motions including heave, pitch, and roll are translated down the lifting wire, resulting in submerged loads being accelerated in response to forces induced by ship motions, with peak tension equal to weight plus inertial effects plus drag effects.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The DLF further increases when lifting objects underwater or through the splash zone.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] For offshore lifts, the DLF typically decreases from 1.3 at 100 tonnes to 1.1 at 2500 tonnes as heavier loads require slower, more controlled operations.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Design wind speeds per American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) 7-16 and ISO 4302:2016 are 20 m/s (72 km/h) for in-service conditions and 42 m/s (150 km/h) for out-of-service survival.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The wind force on a load can be calculated as $F_{\text{wind}}=0.613\times C_{d}\times A\times V^{2}$ where $C_{d}$ is the drag coefficient (typically 1.0-2.0 depending on load shape), A is the projected area in m2, and V is wind speed in m/s.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Research demonstrates that human factors significantly influence dynamic loading events during crane operations.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Modern cranes incorporate electronic control systems that limit acceleration rates through "soft start" mechanisms, reducing DLF and improving operational smoothness while reducing mechanical stress on crane components.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] where W is the working load, g is the acceleration of gravity (9.81 m/s²), $m_{\text{wll}}$ is the maximum lifted mass (working load limit or safe working load), and $m_{a}$ is the mass of lifting appliances or parts of the crane that move with the lifted mass.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] where $F_{d}$ is the design force and $\psi$ is the DLF.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] where $V_{R}$ is relative velocity between lifted object and lifting equipment at the time of pick-up, and C is the stiffness of the crane system at the lifting point.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] The relative velocity is dependent on the crane's operational requirements and the system stiffness can be determined by calculation or load deflection tests.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Modern type-approval tests employ sophisticated instrumentation to accurately measure dynamic loads during crane operation.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Load cells provide measurements with ±0.5% accuracy at full scale, while tri-axial accelerometers capable of measuring accelerations up to 100g are mounted on jib sections and load blocks.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] Strain gauges bonded to critical structural members measure stress distribution, and for offshore applications, GPS systems with ±2cm positional accuracy track wave motion compensation.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p01] High-speed data loggers with sampling rates of 500-1000 Hz capture rapid dynamic response peaks that may be missed at lower sampling rates.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The most basic truck-mounted crane configuration is a "boom truck" or "lorry loader", which features a rear-mounted rotating telescopic-boom crane mounted on a commercial truck chassis.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Larger, heavier duty, purpose-built "truck-mounted" cranes are constructed in two parts: the carrier, often called the *lower*, and the lifting component, which includes the boom, called the *upper*.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These are mated together through a turntable, allowing the upper to swing from side to side.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These modern hydraulic truck cranes are usually single-engine machines, with the same engine powering the undercarriage and the crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The upper is usually powered via hydraulics run through the turntable from the pump mounted on the lower.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In older model designs of hydraulic truck cranes, there were two engines.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] One in the lower pulled the crane down the road and ran a hydraulic pump for the outriggers and jacks.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The one in the upper ran the upper through a hydraulic pump of its own.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Many older operators favor the two-engine system due to leaking seals in the turntable of aging newer design cranes.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Hiab invented the world's first hydraulic truck mounted crane in 1947.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The name, Hiab, comes from the commonly used abbreviation of Hydrauliska Industri AB, a company founded in Hudiksvall, Sweden 1944 by Eric Sundin, a ski manufacturer who saw a way to utilize a truck's engine to power loader cranes through the use of hydraulics.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Generally, these cranes are able to travel on highways, eliminating the need for special equipment to transport the crane unless weight or other size constrictions are in place such as local laws.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] If this is the case, most larger cranes are equipped with either special trailers to help spread the load over more axles or are able to disassemble to meet requirements.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Often a crane will be followed by another truck hauling the counterweights that are removed for travel.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In addition some cranes are able to remove the entire upper.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] However, this is usually only an issue in a large crane and mostly done with a conventional crane such as a Link-Belt HC-238.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] When working on the job site, outriggers are extended horizontally from the chassis then vertically to level and stabilize the crane while stationary and hoisting.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Many truck cranes have slow-travelling capability (a few miles per hour) while suspending a load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Great care must be taken not to swing the load sideways from the direction of travel, as most anti-tipping stability then lies in the stiffness of the chassis suspension.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Most cranes of this type also have moving counterweights for stabilization beyond that provided by the outriggers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Loads suspended directly aft are the most stable, since most of the weight of the crane acts as a counterweight.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Factory-calculated charts (or electronic safeguards) are used by crane operators to determine the maximum safe loads for stationary (outriggered) work as well as (on-rubber) loads and travelling speeds.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Truck cranes range in lifting capacity from about 14.5 short tons (12.9 long tons; 13.2 t) to about 2,240 short tons (2,000 long tons; 2,032 t).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Although most only rotate about 180 degrees, the more expensive truck mounted cranes can turn a full 360 degrees.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A loader crane (also called a *knuckle-boom crane* or *articulating crane*) is a hydraulically powered articulated arm fitted to a truck or trailer, and is used for loading/unloading the vehicle cargo.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The numerous jointed sections can be folded into a small space when the crane is not in use.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] One or more of the sections may be telescopic.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Often the crane will have a degree of automation and be able to unload or stow itself without an operator's instruction.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Unlike most cranes, the operator must move around the vehicle to be able to view his load; hence modern cranes may be fitted with a portable cabled or radio-linked control system to supplement the crane-mounted hydraulic control levers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In the United Kingdom and Canada, this type of crane is often known colloquially as a "Hiab", partly because this manufacturer invented the loader crane and was first into the UK market, and partly because the distinctive name was displayed prominently on the boom arm.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A **rolloader** crane is a loader crane mounted on a chassis with wheels.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Because the crane can move on the trailer, it can be a light crane, so the trailer is allowed to transport more goods.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A telescopic crane has a boom that consists of a number of tubes fitted one inside the other.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A hydraulic cylinder or other powered mechanism extends or retracts the tubes to increase or decrease the total length of the boom.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These types of booms are often used for short term construction projects, rescue jobs, lifting boats in and out of the water, etc.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The relative compactness of telescopic booms makes them adaptable for many mobile applications.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Though not all telescopic cranes are mobile cranes, many of them are truck-mounted.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A telescopic tower crane has a telescopic mast and often a superstructure (jib) on top so that it functions as a tower crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Some telescopic tower cranes also have a telescopic jib.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A rough terrain crane has a boom mounted on an undercarriage atop four rubber tires that is designed for off-road pick-and-carry operations.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Outriggers are used to level and stabilize the crane for hoisting.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These telescopic cranes are single-engine machines, with the same engine powering the undercarriage and the crane, similar to a crawler crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The engine is usually mounted in the undercarriage rather than in the upper, as with crawler crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Most have 4 wheel drive and 4 wheel steering for traversing tighter and slicker terrain than a standard truck crane, with less site prep.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] An all-terrain crane is a hybrid combining the roadability of a truck-mounted and on-site maneuverability of a rough-terrain crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] It can both travel at speed on public roads and maneuver on rough terrain at the job site using all-wheel and crab steering.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] AT's have 2–12 axles and are designed for lifting loads up to 2,000 tonnes (2,205 short tons; 1,968 long tons).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A crawler crane has its boom mounted on an undercarriage fitted with a set of crawler tracks that provide both stability and mobility.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Crawler cranes range in lifting capacity from about 40 to 4,000 long tons (44.8 to 4,480.0 short tons; 40.6 to 4,064.2 t) as seen from the XGC88000 crawler crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The main advantage of a crawler crane is its ready mobility and use, since the crane is able to operate on sites with minimal improvement and stable on its tracks without outriggers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Wide tracks spread the weight out over a great area and are far better than wheels at traversing soft ground without sinking in.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A crawler crane is also capable of traveling with a load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Its main disadvantage is its weight, making it difficult and expensive to transport.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Typically a large crawler must be disassembled at least into boom and cab and moved by trucks, rail cars or ships to its next location.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A pick and carry crane is similar to a mobile crane in that is designed to travel on public roads; however, pick and carry cranes have no stabiliser legs or outriggers and are designed to lift the load and carry it to its destination, within a small radius, then be able to drive to the next job.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Pick and carry cranes are popular in Australia, where large distances are encountered between job sites.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] One popular manufacturer in Australia was Franna, who have since been bought by Terex, and now all pick and carry cranes are commonly called "Frannas", even though they may be made by other manufacturers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Nearly every medium- and large-sized crane company in Australia has at least one and many companies have fleets of these cranes.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The capacity range is between 10 and 40 t (9.8 and 39.4 long tons; 11 and 44 short tons) as a maximum lift, although this is much less as the load gets further from the front of the crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Pick and carry cranes have displaced the work usually completed by smaller truck cranes, as the set-up time is much quicker.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Many steel fabrication yards also use pick and carry cranes, as they can "walk" with fabricated steel sections and place these where required with relative ease.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Smaller pick and carry cranes may be based on an articulated tractor chassis, with the boom mounted over the front wheels.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In Australia these are popularly known as "wobbly cranes".
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A carry deck crane is a small 4 wheel crane with a 360-degree rotating boom placed right in the centre and an operators cab located at one end under this boom.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The rear section houses the engine and the area above the wheels is a flat deck.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Very much an American invention the Carry deck can hoist a load in a confined space and then load it on the deck space around the cab or engine and subsequently move to another site.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The Carry Deck principle is the American version of the pick and carry crane and both allow the load to be moved by the crane over short distances.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Telescopic handlers are forklift-like trucks that have a set of forks mounted on a telescoping extendable boom like a crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Early telescopic handlers only lifted in one direction and did not rotate; however, several of the manufacturers have designed telescopic handlers that rotate 360 degrees through a turntable and these machines look almost identical to the Rough Terrain Crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These new 360-degree telescopic handler/crane models have outriggers or stabiliser legs that must be lowered before lifting; however, their design has been simplified so that they can be more quickly deployed.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These machines are often used to handle pallets of bricks and install frame trusses on many new building sites and they have eroded much of the work for small telescopic truck cranes.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Many of the world's armed forces have purchased telescopic handlers and some of these are the much more expensive fully rotating types.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Their off-road capability and their on site versatility to unload pallets using forks, or lift like a crane make them a valuable piece of machinery.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A **block-setting crane** is a form of crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] They were used for installing the large stone blocks used to build breakwaters, moles and stone piers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In 1949, Hans Liebherr built the first mobile tower crane, the *TK10*.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Tower cranes are a modern form of balance crane that consist of the same basic parts.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Fixed to the ground on a concrete slab (and sometimes attached to the sides of structures), tower cranes often give the best combination of height and lifting capacity and are used in the construction of tall buildings.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The base is then attached to the mast which gives the crane its height.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Further, the mast is attached to the slewing unit (gear and motor) that allows the crane to rotate.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] On top of the slewing unit there are three main parts which are: the long horizontal jib (working arm), shorter counter-jib, and the operator's cab.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Optimization of tower crane location in the construction sites has an important effect on material transportation costs of a project, but site operators need to ensure they assess where the jib will oversail the property of other landowners and tenants as it rotates over the site.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Under English law a landowner also owns the airspace above their property and developers will need to agree terms with adjacent property owners before oversailing their land.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The long horizontal jib is the part of the crane that carries the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The counter-jib carries a counterweight, usually of concrete blocks, while the jib suspends the load to and from the center of the crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The crane operator either sits in a cab at the top of the tower or controls the crane by radio remote control from the ground.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In the first case the operator's cab is most usually located at the top of the tower attached to the turntable, but can be mounted on the jib, or partway down the tower.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The lifting hook is operated by the crane operator using electric motors to manipulate wire rope cables through a system of sheaves.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The hook is located on the long horizontal arm to lift the load which also contains its motor.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In order to hook and unhook the loads, the operator usually works in conjunction with a signaller (known as a "dogger", "rigger" or "swamper").
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] They are most often in radio contact, and always use hand signals.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The rigger or dogger directs the schedule of lifts for the crane, and is responsible for the safety of the rigging and loads.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Tower cranes can achieve a height under hook of over 100 metres.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Tower cranes are used extensively in construction and other industry to hoist and move materials.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Tower cranes can be operated by remote control, removing the need for the crane operator to sit in a cab atop the crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Each model and distinctive style of tower crane has a predetermined lifting chart that can be applied to any radii available, depending on its configuration.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Similar to a mobile crane, a tower crane may lift an object of far greater mass closer to its center of rotation than at its maximum radius.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] An operator manipulates several levers and pedals to control each function of the crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] When a tower crane is used in proximity to buildings, roads, power lines, or other tower cranes, a tower crane anti-collision system is used.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] This operator support system reduces the risk of a dangerous interaction occurring between a tower crane and another structure.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In some countries, such as France, tower crane anti-collision systems are mandatory.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Generally a type of pedestrian operated tower crane, self-erecting tower cranes are transported as a single unit and can be assembled by a qualified technician without the assistance of a larger mobile crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] They are bottom slewing cranes that stand on outriggers, have no counter jib, have their counterweights and ballast at the base of the mast, cannot climb themselves, have a reduced capacity compared to standard tower cranes, and seldom have an operator's cabin.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In some cases, smaller self-erecting tower cranes may have axles permanently fitted to the tower section to make maneuvering the crane onsite easier.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Tower cranes can also use a hydraulic-powered jack frame to raise themselves to add new tower sections without any additional other cranes assisting beyond the initial assembly stage.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] This is how it can grow to nearly any height needed to build the tallest skyscrapers when tied to a building as the building rises.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The maximum unsupported height of a tower crane is around 265 ft.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] For a video of a crane getting taller, see "Crane Building Itself" on YouTube.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] For another animation of such a crane in use, see "SAS Tower Construction Simulation" on YouTube.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Here, the crane is used to erect a scaffold, which, in turn, contains a gantry to lift sections of a bridge spire.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Many tower cranes are designed to "jump" in stages, effectively lifting themselves to the next level.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A reach stacker is a vehicle used for handling intermodal cargo containers in small terminals or medium-sized ports.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Reach stackers are able to transport a container short distances very quickly and pile them in various rows depending on its access.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A sidelifter crane is a road-going truck or semi-trailer, able to hoist and transport ISO standard containers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Container lift is done with parallel crane-like hoists, which can lift a container from the ground or from a railway vehicle.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A travel lift (also called a boat gantry crane, or boat crane) is a crane with two rectangular side panels joined by a single spanning beam at the top of one end.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The crane is mobile with four groups of steerable wheels, one on each corner.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These cranes allow boats with masts or tall super structures to be removed from the water and transported around docks or marinas.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Not to be confused mechanical device used for transferring a vessel between two levels of water, which is also called a boat lift.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A Straddle carrier moves and stacks intermodal containers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] It operates in a way similar to a gantry crane, but its purpose resembles a pick-and-carry crane, since it is used to move containers from one area to another.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Ring cranes are some of the largest and heaviest land-based cranes ever designed.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A ring-shaped track support the main superstructure allowing for extremely heavy loads (up to thousands of tonnes).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In addition to the motions of lifting and revolving, there is provided a so-called "racking" motion, by which the lifting trolley, with the load suspended, can be moved in and out along the jib without altering the level of the load.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Such horizontal movement of the load is a marked feature of later crane design.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These cranes are generally constructed in large sizes and can lift up to 350 tons.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The design of *Hammerkran* evolved first in Germany around the turn of the 19th century and was adopted and developed for use in British shipyards to support the battleship construction program from 1904 to 1914.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The ability of the hammerhead crane to lift heavy weights was useful for installing large pieces of battleships such as armour plate and gun barrels.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Giant cantilever cranes were also installed in naval shipyards in Japan and in the United States.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The British government also installed a giant cantilever crane at the Singapore Naval Base (1938) and later a copy of the crane was installed at Garden Island Naval Dockyard in Sydney (1951).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These cranes provided repair support for the battle fleet operating far from Great Britain.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In the British Empire, the engineering firm Sir William Arrol & Co. was the principal manufacturer of giant cantilever cranes; the company built a total of fourteen.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Among the sixty built in the world, few remain; seven in England and Scotland of about fifteen worldwide.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The Titan Clydebank is one of the four Scottish cranes on the River Clyde and preserved as a tourist attraction.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Normally a crane with a hinged jib will tend to have its hook also move up and down as the jib moves (or *luffs*).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A level luffing crane is a crane of this common design, but with an extra mechanism to keep the hook at the same level when the jib is pivoted in or out.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] An overhead crane, also known as a bridge crane, is a type of crane where the hook-and-line mechanism runs along a horizontal beam that itself runs along two widely separated rails.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Often it is in a long factory building and runs along rails along the building's two long walls.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Overhead cranes typically consist of either a single beam or a double beam construction.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These can be built using typical steel beams or a more complex box girder type.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Pictured on the right is a single bridge box girder crane with the hoist and system operated with a control pendant.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Double girder bridge are more typical when needing heavier capacity systems from 10 tons and above.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The advantage of the box girder type configuration results in a system that has a lower deadweight yet a stronger overall system integrity.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Also included would be a hoist to lift the items, the bridge, which spans the area covered by the crane, and a trolley to move along the bridge.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The most common overhead crane use is in the steel industry.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] At every step of the manufacturing process, until it leaves a factory as a finished product, steel is handled by an overhead crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Raw materials are poured into a furnace by crane, hot steel is stored for cooling by an overhead crane, the finished coils are lifted and loaded onto trucks and trains by overhead crane, and the fabricator or stamper uses an overhead crane to handle the steel in his factory.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The automobile industry uses overhead cranes for handling of raw materials.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Smaller workstation cranes handle lighter loads in a work-area, such as CNC mill or saw.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Almost all paper mills use bridge cranes for regular maintenance requiring removal of heavy press rolls and other equipment.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The bridge cranes are used in the initial construction of paper machines because they facilitate installation of the heavy cast iron paper drying drums and other massive equipment, some weighing as much as 70 tons.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] In many instances the cost of a bridge crane can be largely offset with savings from not renting mobile cranes in the construction of a facility that uses a lot of heavy process equipment.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] This electric overhead traveling crane is most common type of overhead crane, found in many factories.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These cranes are electrically operated by a control pendant, radio/IR remote pendant, or from an operator cabin attached to the crane.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A gantry crane has a hoist in a fixed machinery house or on a trolley that runs horizontally along rails, usually fitted on a single beam (mono-girder) or two beams (twin-girder).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The crane frame is supported on a gantry system with equalized beams and wheels that run on the gantry rail, usually perpendicular to the trolley travel direction.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] These cranes come in all sizes, and some can move very heavy loads, particularly the extremely large examples used in shipyards or industrial installations.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A special version is the container crane (or "Portainer" crane, named by the first manufacturer), designed for loading and unloading ship-borne containers at a port.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A jib crane is a type of crane - not to be confused with a crane rigged with a jib to extend its main boom - where a horizontal member (*jib* or *boom*), supporting a moveable hoist, is fixed to a wall or to a floor-mounted pillar.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Jib cranes are used in industrial premises and on military vehicles.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The jib may swing through an arc, to give additional lateral movement, or be fixed.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Similar cranes, often known simply as hoists, were fitted on the top floor of warehouse buildings to enable goods to be lifted to all floors.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Bulk-handling cranes are designed from the outset to carry a shell grab or bucket, rather than using a hook and a sling.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] They are used for bulk cargoes, such as coal, minerals, scrap metal etc.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A crane with a forklift type mechanism used in automated (computer-controlled) warehouses (known as an automated storage and retrieval system (AS/RS)).
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The crane moves on a track in an aisle of the warehouse.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The fork can be raised or lowered to any of the levels of a storage rack and can be extended into the rack to store and retrieve the product.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The product can in some cases be as large as an automobile.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Stacker cranes are often used in the large freezer warehouses of frozen food manufacturers.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] This automation avoids requiring forklift drivers to work in below-freezing temperatures every day.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Floating cranes are used mainly in bridge building and port construction, but they are also used for occasional loading and unloading of especially heavy or awkward loads on and off ships.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Some floating cranes are mounted on pontoons, others are specialized crane barges with a lifting capacity exceeding 10,000 short tons (8,929 long tons; 9,072 t) and have been used to transport entire bridge sections.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Floating cranes have also been used to salvage sunken ships.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Crane vessels are often used in offshore construction.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The largest revolving cranes can be found on SSCV *Sleipnir*, which has two cranes with a capacity of 10,000 tonnes (11,023 short tons; 9,842 long tons) each.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] For 50 years, the largest such crane was "Herman the German" at the Long Beach Naval Shipyard, one of three constructed by Nazi Germany and captured in the war.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The crane was sold to the Panama Canal in 1996 where it is now known as *Titan*.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Deck cranes, also known as shipboard or cargo cranes, are located on ships and boats, used for cargo operations where no shore unloading facilities are available, raising and lowering loads (such as shellfish dredges and fish nets) into the water, and small boat unloading and retrieval.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Most are diesel-hydraulic or electric-hydraulic, supporting an increasingly automated control interface.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] A railroad crane has flanged wheels for use on railroads.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The simplest form is a crane mounted on a flatcar.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Different types of crane are used for maintenance work, recovery operations and freight loading in goods yards and scrap handling facilities.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Aerial cranes or "sky cranes" usually are helicopters designed to lift large loads.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Helicopters are able to travel to and lift in areas that are difficult to reach by conventional cranes.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Helicopter cranes are most commonly used to lift loads onto shopping centers and high-rise buildings.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] They can lift anything within their lifting capacity, such as air conditioning units, cars, boats, swimming pools, etc.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] They also perform disaster relief after natural disasters for clean-up, and during wild-fires they are able to carry huge buckets of water to extinguish fires.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Some aerial cranes, mostly concepts, have also used lighter-than air aircraft, such as airships.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] Lifetime of existing cranes made of welded metal structures can often be extended for many years by after treatment of welds.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] During development of cranes, load level (lifting load) can be significantly increased by taking into account the IIW recommendations, leading in most cases to an increase of the permissible lifting load and thus to an efficiency increase.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] The generally accepted definition of a crane is a machine for lifting and moving heavy objects by means of ropes or cables suspended from a movable arm.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] As such, a lifting machine that does not use cables, or else provides only vertical and not horizontal movement, cannot strictly be called a 'crane'.
[src:block-and-tackle/crane-machine-p02] More technically advanced types of such lifting machines are often known as "cranes", regardless of the official definition of the term.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] A **deadeye** is an item used in the standing and running rigging of traditional sailing ships.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] It is a smallish round thick wooden (usually lignum vitae) disc with one or more holes through it, perpendicular to the plane of the disc.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] Single and triple-hole deadeyes are most commonly seen.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] The three-holed blocks were called deadeyes because the position of the three holes resemble the eye and nose sockets of a sheep's skull.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] Single deadeyes (or **bull's eyes**) are used to guide and control a line and, particularly in older vessels, to change its direction.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] More modern systems would use a block for this purpose but in traditional rigs with many lines to deal with, designed when blocks were relatively expensive to make, a deadeye provided an acceptable compromise.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] When blocks came into common use for adjusting running rigging, deadeyes continued to be used for tensioning standing rigging.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] Triple deadeyes are used in pairs; a line called a lanyard is run back and forth between them, through the holes, so that they function again much as a block and tackle would.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] This provides a mechanical advantage, pulling harder on whatever the deadeyes are attached to.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] Pairs of deadeyes are placed in the shrouds (the lines that hold up the mast), where they are used to create greater tension in the shrouds.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] To set up the lanyards used with dead-eyes, a suitable grease such as tallow is first applied to the holes.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] After reeving the lanyard through the deadeyes, the end is hooked to a handy purchase in the rig above, such as the throat halyard.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] By hauling on the halyard the lanyard in the deadeyes is drawn up taut.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] A small wooden wedge is knocked into the last hole, to prevent the lanyard sliding back, and the end is unhooked from the purchase and made up on the shroud above the upper deadeye.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] The wedge can then be removed ready for the next shroud.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] As an alternative the tackle on the lanyard can be made fast to the shroud well above the upper deadeye so that it compresses the deadeyes.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] The last part of the lanyard can then be seized to an adjacent part between the deadeyes.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] When this is finished the tackle is cast off and the lanyard made off.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] In recent decades, as steel wire became the prevalent material for sailboat rigging, deadeyes and lanyards gave way to metal turnbuckles for tensioning the wires.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] More recently, however, with the advent of high-strength and low-stretch synthetic fibres, some sailboats are using synthetic rope for standing rigging, and deadeyes and lanyards are coming back into use as tensioning devices.
[src:block-and-tackle/deadeye] Modern deadeyes, also known as *chainplate distributors* can be made of titanium or aluminum, manufactured by vendors such as Colligo Marine.
